Much of the gumshoes discovery happened by luck and chance rather than logic. Green ears? Green paint? A painter! The sudden rush of clues, leading neatly to the serial killer via work permits and job orders via computer, felt a bit pat after all the soul-searching, existential doubt and flashback interviewing.



The final scenes, with McConaughey dressed, positioned and coiffed to look like Jesus Christ, suggested more profundity than the show actually offered. Looking to the night sky for cosmic truths, Hart (Harrelson) and Cohle (McConaughey) again slip away from the authority figures (this time, its the hospital) to go it alone. Together.



Its all about good versus evil, light versus dark, Cohle concluded, and the lights winning.



Moody, unnerving, confusing  but surprisingly optimistic.



HBO Go crash



Meanwhile, the light may have been ascendant, but the electrons werent cooperating: The HBO Go streaming service collapsed, unable to feed demand for the finale Sunday. The network promptly scheduled a rerun, and the service on HBO cable was unaffected. The twitterverse had a field day (sample tweet: Congratulations to #TrueDetective for being the first show to literally break @HBOGO).





A mystery wrapped in a religious cult conspiracy, slowly unfolded by two antiheroes  one a lying adulterer, the other an addict with pretentious theories about the meaning of life  ultimately was a male drama. The mission involved saving little girls, balancing the loss of one of the detectives little girl. But women didnt figure in, except as a plot twist to establish the two detectives antipathy.



Woody Harrelson and Matthew McConaughey deserve applause, the creepy littered overgrown and horrific compound where the endgame played out deserves a nod for set design; T Bone Burnett deserves praise for the moody, even otherworldly music. But storywise, the eight episodes of this anthology series involved too many leaps and loopholes. The misdirection concerning the suspected pedophile priest, the Rev. Billy Lee Tuttle, was just confusing. How did he die? What did it matter?

