HBO’s superb ‘True Detective’ finale Delivers the “scented meat” and a promise of an unkillable character who had a profound emotional breakdown in the last scenes.‘True Detective’s’ Cohle and Hart Hopefully Will Reunite Down the Road, Some Thoughts – JIm Bridges/Jim Bridges/HBO – Woody Harrelson and Matthew McConaughey in HBO’s “True Detective.”Years ago, I shared a row on a plane heading to Washington DC with a woman who was in law enforcement. She eventually let it be known her local police work went from victim’s advocacy to actually working with detectives on child abuse cases that were sexual in nature. Her persistent work elevated her to a task force on the Federal level, and though she couldn’t be specific, she had a touch of the possessed Matthew McConaughey’s character Rust Cohle in her. She told me they could only chip away at the sloppy ones, but there were so many well-connected, politically powerful and rich men the world over in this game of collecting and sharing child porn, it had permanently changed her outlook on life and having a family of her own.Sunday’s finale of “True Detective” was intense, gripping, moody and creepy, and it underscored the whack-a-mole nature of the very clever pedophile who connects with like-minded in the service of protecting their very disturbing fetish/crimes. The eight-episode murder-mystery series took us to the coastal Louisiana where good ol’ boys and family political power were able to mask and gag some of the dirty family business. It’s an environment where someone can disappear really easily and not too many questions seem to get asked.“True Detective” also reveals the pitch-perfect chemistry for two Texas born actors, Matthew McConaughey and Woody Harrelson, who together remind so many critics of Redford and Newman. That elusive heterosexual bromance exists for them, one that makes us want to watch them order a burger and chit-chat, let alone solve crimes.McConaughey took his Cohle down the Zen dickhead path, unable to process his grief and loss of his daughter, and Harrelson’s Hart comes to grips after losing everything because he is such a liar in denial. His lies wedge away his family and he is left with Cohle, each man broken and lacking in different but complimentary ways.The entire narrative of this leg of “True Detective” is underscored with the masks and lies we all wear to protect ourselves in daily life, whether its raw emotions, ability to square the truth with oneself or prison or worse for the evil that dwells in some.This juicy tale telling is from Nic Pizzolatto, whose potboiler Louisiana whodunnit with T. Bone Burnett’s haunting score and detectives Rust Cohle (McConaughey) and Marty Hart (Harrelson) has created a demand for the two to reunite somehow in a future run of the series, which will emulate the anthology style of “American Horror Story” with different casts and tales to solve.The series with Rust and Marty focused on a serial killer with a protected layer of well-connected types who have obfuscated evidence and information to shield the perverted desires of some very wealthy men.  Charismatic power has served our killer, preying on the young and poor who can easily be poached. Strange symbolic pagan art and twig structures define their killing grounds, laying markers for those who understand the portentousness.The production design for the labyrinth and lair of the Yellow King must be remembered for an award for excellence. The crafts often get overlooked in write ups, but Production Design Alex DiGerlando, Art Director Tim Beach and Mara LePere-Schloop and Set Decorator Cynthia Anne Slagter all deserve major kudos for drawing us into this Southern Gothic hell on earth that made us feel we had Spanish Moss creeping up on our leg.There is no plan at present for McConaughey or Harrelson to reunite these characters. But a strange alchemy occurred in the making of this series that is undeniable. We love when actors connect so genuinely, and make us laugh when the situation is grim. Hart is relatable for many men who screw up a good thing and hurt women they love, and Cohle breaks through and feels the loss finally of his child, cracking the medicated (booze and drugs) veneer of his driven detective who lives to work. Their foibles and flaws cement these characters as memorable for the ages, just like Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.We all hope to see the “unkillable” Cohle and Hart chip away further at the cancerous mass of these concealed animals who are under the surface of our society still, lurking and waiting for opportunity. Got something to say about this? Tell us in the comments!RE: TANIC Goddess Misterious CrossRe Barry Fell: He was blackballed by academic community...By Helenita, 4 hours  agobilayeno Master heroI've been watching and digesting of all the various asp...By bilayeno, 1 day  agoRE: TANIC Goddess Misterious CrossHey Chris  and Everybody else.. New to the Forum and ho...By GrammyJo, 3 days  agoNolan's CrossI've been watching and digesting all the various aspect...By SandraV, 3 days  ago
